    The <fr:em>mapping cone</fr:em> construction for morphisms of simplicial sets works in the same way for simplicial objects in any category <fr:tex>\mathscr {C}</fr:tex> that has a final object <fr:tex>e</fr:tex> and finite sums.
    For <fr:tex>u\colon  Y_\bullet \to  X_\bullet </fr:tex>, the cone <fr:tex>C(u)</fr:tex> satisfies
    <fr:tex
display="block">       C(u)_n       = X_n{\,\textstyle \coprod \,}\coprod _{i&lt;n} Y_i{\,\textstyle \coprod \,}e.     </fr:tex></fr:p><fr:p>
    We take <fr:tex>\mathscr {C}</fr:tex> to be:

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        the category of topological spaces and continuous maps, with final object <fr:tex>e=P^t</fr:tex>;
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        the category of pairs <fr:tex>(X,F)</fr:tex> where <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> is a topological space and <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> is an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>, with an arrow <fr:tex>(u,f)\colon (Y,F)\to (X,G)</fr:tex> consisting of a continuous map <fr:tex>u\colon  Y\to  X</fr:tex> and a <fr:tex>u</fr:tex>-morphism (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.5"
href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.5.xml"
number="5.1.5"></fr:ref>) <fr:tex>f\colon  G\to  F</fr:tex>, with final object <fr:tex>e=(P^t,0)</fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
